Incident Summary:

On my lab environment, I simulated and analyzed a Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS)–like activity targeting a web service. The objective was to observe abnormal traffic patterns, validate detection mechanisms, and document the response workflow. The activity resulted in a noticeable spike in incoming requests, impacting service responsiveness.

Incident Details
Date/Time: 2026-02-04T23:01:32.185184+05:30
Incident Type: DDoS Attack (Simulated)
Target System: Web server hosted on local/VM environment
Detection Source: SIEM dashboard / Network monitoring logs
Severity: High

Detection:

During monitoring, I observed a sudden surge in network traffic directed at the web server. Key indicators included:

High volume of repeated requests within a short time interval
Multiple requests originating from the same or multiple IPs
Increased server response time and temporary unavailability

The alert was triggered based on abnormal traffic thresholds configured in the monitoring system.

Analysis:

Upon further investigation:

Logs showed continuous HTTP requests targeting the same endpoint
Traffic pattern indicated automated or scripted behavior
No valid user interaction patterns (e.g., no session diversity, repeated identical requests)

This confirmed the activity as a simulated DDoS/flooding scenario rather than normal user traffic.

Action Taken:
Monitored incoming traffic to confirm persistence of attack pattern
Identified source IP(s) generating excessive requests
Applied temporary blocking (if configured) or noted mitigation steps
Verified system stability after traffic normalization

Impact:
Temporary degradation in server performance
Increased response latency
No permanent damage or data loss observed

Recovery:
System performance returned to normal after stopping simulated traffic
Logs verified no continued abnormal activity
Monitoring continued for a defined period to ensure stability

Lessons Learned:
Threshold-based alerting is effective for detecting volumetric attacks
Visualization dashboards help quickly identify traffic anomalies
Basic rate-limiting and IP blocking can mitigate simple flooding attacks
Need for advanced protections (e.g., WAF, load balancing) in real environments
